       #include <strings.h>

       char *index(const char *s, int *c);

       char *rindex(const char *s, int *c);

DDeessccrriippttiioonn
       These  functions operate on NULL-terminated strings.  They
       do not check for overflow of any receiving string.

       index and rindex return a  pointer  to  the  first  (last)
       occurrence  of  character c in string s, or a NULL pointer
       if c does not occur in the  string.   The  NULL  character
       terminating  a  string  is  considered  to  be part of the
       string.

